sec.p:
Previous studies have revealed high species diversity of Aureoboletus in China (
Yang et al . 2003
; Shi & Liu 2013 ;
Zhang et al . 2014
, 2015a ,b, 2017, 2019;
Zeng et al . 2015
;
Wu et al . 2016
;
Wang et al . 2020
). The three new lineages identified in this study were described as new species: A. guangdongensis , A. microcarpus , and A. rugosus .
Zhang et al . (2019)
proposed eight major clades (I–VIII) of Aureoboletus on the basis of morphological features and phylogenetic inference. Our molecular data indicated that A. guangdongensis is nested within Clade II (
), whereas A. microcarpus and A. rugosus are nested within Clade III.

Concerning the ecological preference, the three new species, viz. A. guangdongensis , A. microcarpus , and A. rugosus grow in oak forests; all others in China are also associated with fagaceous trees, except A. mirabili s (Murrill 1912: 98) Halling (2015: 19) , which grows in subalpine forests (
Yang et al . 2003
; Shi & Liu 2013 ;
Zhang et al . 2014
, 2015a ,b, 2017, 2019;
Zeng et al . 2015
;
Wu et al . 2016
;
Wang et al . 2020
). Unsurprisingly, most Aureoboletus species
outside of China also grow in oak forests ( Frost 1874 ; Patouillard, 1895 ; Klofac 2010 ;
Zeng et al . 2015
; GarcíaJiménez et al . 2019; Kuo & Ortiz-Santana 2020; Farid et al . 2021).

We also noted that all Aureoboletus species
are from the northern Hemisphere, except A. novoguineensis Hongo (1973: 544)
from Papua New Guinea (
) (
Yang et al . 2003
; Klofac 2010 ; Shi & Liu 2013 ;
Zhang et al . 2014
, 2015a , b, 2017, 2019;
Halling et al . 2015
;
Zeng et al . 2015
;
Wu et al . 2016
; Kuo & Ortiz-Santana 2020;
Wang et al . 2020
; Farid et al . 2021). In the northern Hemisphere, more than half the Aureoboletus species
occur in Asia; species diversity is also high in North America, with 16 Aureoboletus taxa described to date ( Frost 1874 ; Patouillard 1895 ; Klofac 2010 ;
Halling et al . 2015
;
García-Jiménez et al . 2019
; Kuo & Ortiz-Santana 2020; Farid et al . 2021); in Europe, only four taxa, viz. A. gentilis (Quél.) Pouzar
, A. moravicus , A. moravicus f . luteus Nonis & Ponzi
, and A. moravicus f . pallescens (Herink) Klofac
have been described ( Klofac 2010 ).

